(Real Learning Application) Tj
T*
(In real study situations, students master Computer Basics by practising with tasks that) Tj
T*
(mirror identifying system components and their functions. The topic becomes more) Tj
T*
(meaningful when it is linked to examples, revision drills, and exam-style questions that) Tj
T*
(reflect how Computer Science is assessed.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(Worked Examples) Tj
T*
(Worked Example 1) Tj
T*
(1. Start with an example based on tracing how data enters, is processed, and is) Tj
T*
(displayed.) Tj
T*
(2. Identify the exact idea in hardware, software, input, processing, storage, and output) Tj
T*
(that the question is testing.) Tj
T*
(3. Apply the correct method for Computer Basics step by step without skipping reasoning.) Tj
T*
(4. Check the final answer and explain why it is correct.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(Worked Example 2) Tj
T*
(1. Choose a second example that still focuses on identifying system components and their) Tj
T*
(functions.) Tj
T*
(2. Break the task into smaller parts and link each part to the rule being used.) Tj
T*
(3. Point out how to avoid mixing hardware devices with software programs while solving) Tj
T*
(it.) Tj
T*
(4. Review the result and connect it back to the topic overview.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(Common Mistakes) Tj
T*
(- Misunderstanding the core focus of Computer Basics: hardware, software, input,) Tj
T*
(processing, storage, and output.) Tj
T*
(- Mixing hardware devices with software programs.) Tj
T*
(- Jumping to an answer without showing the steps or reasoning clearly.) Tj
T*
(- Practising Computer Basics without checking whether the method matches the question) Tj
T*
(being asked.) Tj
